(107, 105, 'The proof of concept is to show that NCHS DOQS (Customized version of IBIS-PH) can produce reports that derive from summarization of complex data for which its basis is public-use data.  The objective is that these reports allow for readers to have access to comprehensible information on vital statistical data in a compact publication.  A goal of NCHS DOQS is to provide the public with capabilities to define queries that yield results from real time processing and not from pre-tabulated data.  The challenge is to test the feasibility of NCHS DOQS being able to process thousands of variable crossings in deriving at statistical analysis upon request in a reasonable time period. \r\n\r\nThe COT Software, IBIS-PH, which is an open source that runs on Apache/Tomcat (also open source) with a SAS server backend.  Because IBIS-PH is Open source software, it is necessary to utilize this lab to prototype different configurations and develop project capabilities for the purpose of determining feasibilities and possible associated risks while operating inside the CDC network.\r\n', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(110, 108, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(111, 109, 'The goal of the project is to create a means for all interested individuals or organizations to get an in-depth understanding of the functionalities and capabilities of the NBS application. This will allow any reporting jurisdiction interested in adopting the system to â€œtest driveâ€ it. Non production data will be used as a sample. Our project requires the use of the lab so that the application can be accessible both within the CDC network and also externally to the public.', '', 'State and local public health departments', 'Application users, data suppliers/ data recipients', 'State and local public health laboratories', 'Application users, data suppliers', 'CDC Programs', 'Data recipients', 'CDC and non-CDC public health Subject matter experts', 'Data users', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(112, 110, 'The objective of the EPI-X Data Communication Project is to look at the different ways that EPI-X users can transfer data (send and receive). The focus is the transference of data between EPI-X users in the US, Canada and Mexico. When an EPI-X user enters or updates information on EPI-X forms, regardless of their location, the changes should be seen by all EPI-X users. \r\n\r\nThe following data communication options of data sharing server-to-server have been identified at this time. \r\n\r\n1)	Fist option - Look at Web Services or WCF as the tools to use to communicate between servers. This functionality will allow for a more secure method of data transference.\r\n\r\nïƒ¼	Challenge â€“ Is to implement and publish web services on servers in the 3 countries (US, Canada and Mexico). The security requirements will need to be identified for each country.\r\n\r\n2)	Second option â€“ Look at using a FTP site. This functionality will allow for Data files to be uploaded through a secured FTP site in the following formats (XML, Excel).  The required application will read the uploaded file and transfer the data between servers..\r\n\r\nUsers=\r\nDarshan Trivedi	ius9@cdc.gov\r\nPoorvi Bhatt	Jty1@cdc.gov\r\nVamshi Thatipamula jpu4@cdc.gov', 'Ability to collaborate via data between three countries (US, Canada, Mexico) on predefined data structure.  The Epi-X Data Communication will enable who share a common exchanging of information in order to advance their missions, and provides a foundation for information exchange between. ', 'Ronald Abernathy DEO', 'IT Project Manager', 'Clarence Bloomfield DEO Lockheed Contractor', 'Technical Steward', 'EA', 'NIEM SME', 'Georgia Tech', 'NIEM SME', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(113, 111, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(114, 112, 'Goal: Test Mocana MAP to ensure the product works as designed, meets service utility and warranty expectations and is in fact suitable for use in meeting security requirements.\r\nChallenges: Secure data collection as defined by NIST cannot achieve natively on iOS or Android mobile device operating systems.\r\nOpportunities: A third-party solution such as Mocana MAP may provide the level of protection that meets OMB requirements\r\nVision: Provide CDC Program software developers the tools to protect the mobile applications they develop.\r\nTechnologies: FIPS validated encryption module, administrative console, CMDA, Wi-Fi, LAN, Mobile devices (iOS, Android), access to the lab via the internet, Content Management System access\r\n', 'Jaspal Sagoo	Jzs2@cdc.gov\r\n\r\nEarl Baum	Eeb9@cdc.gov\r\nCharles Martin	Gwe0@cdc.gov\r\n\r\nITSO Security	\r\nOCISO	\r\nINTS	\r\n', 'INTS Co-Chairs', 'IT Innovation', 'INTS Co-Chairs', 'Enterprise Services Committee', 'INTS Co-Chairs', 'IRGC', 'CDC Programs', 'CDC Programs', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(115, 113, 'Goal: to determine if our current HD audio/video conversion equipment can be used to live stream into webinar software.\r\n\r\nChallenges: getting the InstantPresenter webinar software to recognize our converted HD A/V stream as an IP webcam\r\n\r\nOpportunities: cutting costs by precluding the need of purchasing additional A/V hardware to live stream into webinar software\r\n\r\nOverall project vision: to cost effectively provide video streaming opportunities within Virtual Instances (VIs) (VIs are individual occurrences of virtual events, expos, conferences, offices or other business portals).\r\n\r\nData: We are building off of the example of last yearâ€™s PHI Virtual Conference, where a contracted A/V company was able to convert a live broadcast signal into an IP signal â€“ effectively streaming a converted HD video feed into the InstantPresenter webinar software. They did this using a live video switcher and a live streaming box (with an Ethernet output) into a PC. Hypothetically, we should be able to mimic the same result using our MOTU HDX-SDI rackmount unitâ€™s live video codex conversion capabilities, outputting the signal through a HD output and our computer video cardâ€™s HD input. Hopefully, the resulting signal will be recognized as an IP webcam.\r\n\r\nTechnologies: VPI programming platform, HD PCI Express video card, MOTU HDX-SDI rackmount unit, InstantPresenter webinar software, Adobe Premiere Pro software\r\n\r\nImpacted Use Cases: future initiatives utilizing VPI technology services\r\n\r\nWhy we need the Informatics R&D lab services: to utilize an off-network, wireless internet connection with our off-network computer and A/V hardware\r\n', '', 'Oona Powell, ADC Director (OSELS/PHSIPO/OD/Communications) ', 'Governing ', 'Adam Arthur, VPI Team Lead/Business Steward (OSELS/PHSIPO/OD/Communications/VPI)', 'Key Technology User/Tester', 'Phil Carner, VPI Team Member', 'Key Technology User/Tester', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(151, 149, 'â€¢	PHINMS (Public Health Information Network Messaging System) is a system that securely sends and receives encrypted data to and from public health information systems using Electronic Business Extensible Markup Language technology over the Internet. Additional information can be accessed using the following link.\r\nhttp://www.cdc.gov/phin/tools/PHINms/index.html\r\n\r\nâ€¢	Currently, the PHINMS application does not have a Linux environment to support PHINMS Linux deployments.  Several PHINMS customers would like to deploy the new PHINMS version 2.2.08 in Linux environment. \r\nâ€¢	The PHINMS development team would like to have a Linux environment to research and create Linux based scripts to automate installation and deployment of PHINMS applications in Linux platform.\r\n', 'State, county and local public health centers	User\r\nPrivate hospitals and clinics 	User \r\nAcademic and research institutions 	User\r\n', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(116, 114, 'CDC partners use and develop different open source applications software to support data collection and information management systems to support DGHA/CDC missions. These open source software are used only by CDC partners and not intended to install on CDC network and hence do not require any C&A approval.  PHITPOâ€™s R&D virtual servers will be used to review and test these applications. Please note that these servers will act as a test environment and will not contain any PII. ', '', 'Dave Cross', 'Team Leader, System Strengthening Team, ILB/DGHA/CGH ', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(119, 117, 'Background and Problem: MINOS is a system for epidemiologic surveillance and project monitoring for Medecins Sans Frontieres (MSF) Operational Center of Brussels (OCB). Data on MSFâ€™s patients and interventions are collected at the point of care, entered into a local database in the field and exported to higher level databases in the mission capital and the headquarters in Brussels. MINOS prepares standard project indicators with this information and displays their trends over time. While this system is being developed by MSF-OCB, it has been accepted in principle as the future medical data management for the entire MSF movement. MSF has five operational centers located in Amsterdam, Barcelona, Brussels, Geneva, and Paris. These manage over 23 national entities with projects spread over 60 countries. This system has been pilot tested in the field but not yet had more widespread implementation. While the system is still in a formative stage, it would be good to have an external evaluation to guide its further development. MSF OCB has requested that the CDC Public Health Informatics Fellowship Program conduct this Evaluation to:\r\n\r\nProject Objective: Assess the current data model, system architecture and user interface (PHAEDRA) of MINOS and provide recommendations to improve the same. \r\n\r\nRequirement: The MINOS system cannot be accessed on the CMS network and will require a virtual machine (VM) to assess the user interface.\r\n', '', 'Medecins Sans Frontieres  Operational Center of Brussels', 'MINOS Developers', 'Public Health Informatics Fellowship Program (PHIFP)', 'Evaluators', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(120, 118, 'The CDC Global AIDS Program (GAP) Data Management Team (DMT) will be providing support for PEPFAR countries in terms of fundamental data and spatial data management to support HIV AIDS free generation goals over the next 2 years.   Data management and spatial data management will require some GIS skills, software, training, and international language support, etc.   The GAP Data Management team would like a sandbox to test various open source GIS apps.', '', 'CDC GAP Data Mgt Team', 'CDC Global AIDS Program', 'CDC Country mgrs and teams.', 'CDC Global AIDS Program', 'CDC staff in low resource areas', 'CDC Global AIDS Program', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(121, 119, 'The primary goal is to get user feedback on a new web-based tool that they can use to search for case definitions and the annual lists of Nationally Notifiable Conditions. ', '', 'Ruth Jajosky (OSELS/PHSIPO/DNDHI)', 'SME', 'Aaron Aranas (OSELS/PHSIPO/DNDHI)', 'SME', 'CDC Programs', 'User', 'CSTE', 'User', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(122, 120, '', '', 'Mephis DOH', 'User', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(123, 121, 'The vision of Epi Info Web Survey product is to use Epi Info desktop application to create online forms to help CDC programs conduct surveys, gather useful information for analysis and to further expand CDCâ€™s public health mission.\r\nEpi Info Web Survey will enable surveys created using Epi Info desktop application on the web. The survey can be distributed to the targeted audience using emails or any other electronic form. Each survey is accessed using the URL that is unique to a given survey. The web application will allow a survey participant to take a survey. An epidemiologist will be able to download the survey responses from web and analyze the survey data any time during the period the survey is open or after the survey has closed using Epi Info desktop application.  The diagram below summarizes at a high level various use cases being fulfilled by the Epi Info Web Survey system.\r\n', 'The Epi Info Web Survey product enables following functionalities on the web.\r\n-	Provide services to allow publishing a survey created using Epi Info Desktop on the web.\r\n-	Dynamically reproduce on the web the survey that has been created and published from Epi Info desktop. The Epi Info Web Survey product supports survey created using following controls: Label, single line text box, multi-line text box, numeric text box, date picker, check box and group box\r\n-	The Epi Info Web Survey product supports skip logic by its ability to hide, unhide, highlight, un-highlight, enable and disable survey questions. It also supports navigation logic.\r\n-	Survey participant is able to access the survey, complete the survey in one session or save the responses and complete it a later time. They can submit the survey upon completion.\r\n-	Provide services to download the survey responses collected on the web into Epi Info Desktop for analysis.\r\nThe Epi Info Web Survey system comprises of following infrastructure components:\r\n-	Manger Service: This web service will enable Epi Info desktop to allow publishing the survey on the web and download the survey responses.\r\n-	Data Service: This web service provides the web application data to create surveys at run time and to manage data collected from the survey participant.\r\n-	Web Survey application: This web application creates the survey on the web using the Meta data in the database. It allows survey participant to participate in the survey and provide their response.\r\n-	Web Survey database: The system will consist of a relational database that will store the survey published on the web and store the survey responses provided by the survey participant.   \r\n\r\nWhile software development for Epi Info Web Survey is complete, the team needs an external facing hosting environment to allow stakeholders to begin familiarizing themselves with the new system.  The R&D Laboratory seems well suited for this purpose. In the meantime, the Epi Info Team will continue ushering the system through CDCâ€™s C&A process with the ultimate goal of hosting this product on the public CDC.gov site. \r\n', 'Food borne illness and other CDC programs', 'User / survey publisher / data recipient', 'Field data collector', 'Data supplier / survey participant', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(135, 133, 'Preventing Chronic Disease (PCD) requests the use of an iPad 1 device to continue its development and QA of an iOS application. The team recently lost access to its sole development device, and thus requests the resources of the lab.\r\nPCD works closely with the mobile team in OADC, who will install the development app and subsequent QA builds on the loaner device. The project has been approved by our ISSO and OCISO.\r\nOur goal is to complete testing, submit framework applications, and gain Apple, Inc. approval for iTunes by mid-August, at which point the device will be returned to the lab.', '', 'Kim Bright (NCCDPHP/OD/PCD)', 'IT Project Manager / Developer', 'Alex Casanova (DNEM/OADC)', 'Mobile Team Lead', 'Cassian Pallansch (DNEM/OADC)', 'Mobile Team Tech Lead', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(124, 122, 'NCEH/ATSDR is currently in the planning and process stages of developing native and web-based applications (apps) for emergency responders, field personnel, and others. Initially, these apps will primarily be used  for used to determine human risk exposure to hazardous chemicals and toxic substances.', '', 'Emergency Responders to Hazardous Site', 'User', 'Public Health Workers at Hazardous Sites', 'User', 'Government Epidemiologists', 'User, governing body', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(125, 123, 'The DBS project will use WEAVE, a web-based analysis and visualization development platform, to allow state and local public health departments to leverage BRFSS data by linking with other publicly available data sources from data.gov (e.g. Census, USDA, etc.). \r\nThe project will support multiple levels of user proficiency â€“ novice to advanced â€“ as well as the ability to integrate, disseminate and visualize data at â€œnestedâ€ levels of geography from State to community.\r\nIn addition the project will also enable CDC programs to collaborate with states and communities for making cogent cases for influencing policies and evaluating outcomes over time.\r\n', '', 'DBS', 'User, data supplier, governing body', 'State and local public health departments', 'Users, report recipients', 'Centers, Divisions, Branches and Programs across CDC', 'Users, data suppliers, report recipients', 'Academic researchers', 'Users (advanced)', 'Public at large', 'Users (novice)', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(126, 124, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(127, 125, 'This project will explore and document how to use cross-platform mobile development platforms to create a single code base that deploys as native applications on Android and iOS through the public app stores: Apple iTunes AppStore, Google Play Marketplace. The app will be free.\r\n\r\nThis project expands on the previous two versions of the STD Guidelines app for iOS but will output a fully functioning prototype that displays the 2010 STD Guidelines on smartphones. The Guidelines are publicly available through the CDC web site and the app will not use any new or non-public information.\r\n\r\nThis project will serve as guidance to the multiple programs who have asked how to incorporate mobile computing into their existing web platform for sharing information with their public stakeholders.', '', 'STD Program', 'Content Provider', 'Physicians', 'App Users', 'IRGC Innovation Subcommittee', 'Reviewers', 'CDC Programs', 'Methodology User', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Deliverables include:\r\nSingle code base\r\nDeployment packages for both Android and iOS\r\nGuidance Paper/Brief Review\r\nBlog posts describing development process', ''),
(128, 126, 'This is a follow-up to engagement 31.\r\n\r\nOn 1/27/2011 - ePub version of document prepared and presented to STD team.  VM has been created for them to make edits, and help transition the resource to a production version.  To work with the OD for this transition.  ePub pubished on their site.  http://www.cdc.gov/std/2010-ebook.htm.\r\n\r\nThey will be using Sigil - a multi-platform EPUB ebook editor for making the changes.  They will use this software in a windows VM.', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(131, 129, 'The Web-based Injury Statistics Query and Reporting System (WISQARS, http://www.cdc.gov/injury/wisqars) is operated and managed by the Office of Statistics and Programming (OSP) of the National Center for Injury Prevention and Control (NCIPC). WISQARS is an interactive web-based query system that provides national and state-based injury mortality and national injury morbidity (hospitalizations, ED visits) data to the general public in a timely manner.  More specifically, WISQARS provides historical and current death data from the National Vital Statistics System (NVSS), nonfatal injury data from the National Electronic Injury Surveillance System All Injury Program (NEISS-AIP), and violent death data from the National Violent Death Reporting System (NVDRS).  One of the goals of WISQARS has been to provide user-friendly and readily accessible national and state-level injury-related data, including counts, rates, cost of injury and injury mortality maps.  NCIPC/OSP will be receiving external expertise to assist in the design and development of fully functional WISQARS Injury Mobile Apps for tablets and smart phones.  The Injury Mobile Apps should have the following features: flexibility, user-friendly, provide a snapshot of injury as a public health concern, provide timely updates with current mortality data (SAS-generated downloads to a local data set that feeds the App). The first year will focus on developing a tablet application for the Apple iPad.  The second year will focus on developing a smartphone application to function on an Apple iPhone.  The third year will focus on modifying and adapting these applications to work on other tablets and smartphones (e.g., Android, Windows, and Blackberry Windows devices).', 'The public uses WISQARS (academia/hospitals/trauma centers/surgeons/nurses/etc)	This project is a proof of concept to develop an injury data mobile app that can be used by national and state public health professionals and injury researchers/educators to inform policy makers and the public', 'public', '(academia/hospitals/trauma centers/surgeons/nurses/etc)', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(144, 142, 'Goals\r\nProvide a sandbox environment to demonstrate interoperability mechanisms between health information systems, specifically those for HIV patient based and reporting systems. \r\nChallenges\r\nInteroperability is a moving target. Setting up the messaging mechanism is the core requirement. Determining which functionality provides reasonable coverage for the interoperability requirements is not yet determined. \r\nOpportunities\r\nWhile targeted for CGH/DGHA this interoperability demonstration setup will allow anyone interested in the mechanisms for interoperable health information systems to explore this with some leading open source HIS packages. \r\n', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '');
