(177, 175, 'testing out a new tool which allows entities to request specific countermeasures avaiable only through CDC - e.g, botulism \r\n\r\nOne day UAT session...using the physical lab.', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(178, 176, 'Providing a Reference Implementation will serve Public Health stakeholders to minimize the adoption burden of technologies that facilitate the collection of reportable/notifiable disease information. This project will emulate the technical steps necessary to capture, store, and transmit this information from the point-of-care (electronic medical record) to public health officials (at the Federal level). In order to achieve this, the project will use publicly available, low cost/open source applications to simulate the different electronic components that are involved in this process. We will also rely on existing infrastructure as to reduce the financial burden from the project. We expect the following project outcomes:\r\n1.	Reference Implementation Guide: document that will be made publicly available that will serve as a how-to manual for clinicians / hospitals / public health entities that require reporting of notifiable disease information.\r\n2.	Identification of possible roadblocks / technical challenges faced by clinicians / hospitals / public health entities.\r\n3.	Development of in-house expertise that will be used to assist our stakeholders.\r\nThese outcomes will be made publicly available through phConnect.org. We estimate that the project will last four months and will include primarily members of the Division of Notifiable Diseases and Healthcare Information. In addition, we will use the R&D Laboratory to host one of our servers in order to provide the simulated environment. We do expect to incur in additional costs but only the time spent in preparing the different components, in addition to possible cost of software licenses (when these are not open source / free).\r\n\r\nIn our server, we will simulate (with the use of virtual servers) the different components (applications) that take part in the reporting of notifiable disease information. These components include instances of OpenMRS, OpenELIS, the NEDSS Base System (NBS), a CDC Receiver, a Knowledge Base of Case Definitions and PHINVADS Light.\r\n\r\nAfter setting up all these components, we will identify optimal configurations that will provide guidance to all interested stakeholders.\r\n', '', 'Alan Davis', '', 'Jason Combs', '', 'David King', '', 'Jeffrey Kriseman', '', 'Miguel H. Torres-Urquidy', '', 'Michael Wodajo', '', '', '', '', ''),
(179, 177, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(180, 178, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(181, 179, 'A functional wiki with visitors and eventually contributors within one year.\r\nThe wiki informs the microtasking project which links to CDCâ€™s strategic public health priority for supporting state, tribal, and local health departments in two significant ways. \r\nFirst, providing â€œopportunities for collaboration and strategies for enhancing public healthâ€ with a targeted public audience; secondly, providing a strategy to enhance public health by inviting the public to be involved in CDC projects directly. \r\nThis innovation also supports the prevention of illness, injury, disability, and premature death by alleviating time commitments of small tasks from subject matter experts so that they may â€œprovide better emergency response, expertise, public health infrastructure strengthening, vaccine development, and guidelines for effective interventionsâ€.\r\nThis is an innovative take on the traditional methods for reaching CDC strategic objectives and the developers see multiple impacts that support the entire CDC mission without being tied directly to single initiatives or strategies:\r\n1.	A cultural shift in how CDC staff manage projects, breaking out small tasks that can be crowdsourced. This will lead to a more nimble workforce with the time to focus on their specialties.\r\n2.	Growth in the number of college students interested in public health professions based on insight into ongoing CDC projects. Crowdsourcing to college students should be framed as a precursor to the Public Health Associates Program and the Public Health Prevention Specialist Fellowship.\r\n3.	A new social dialogue with the next generation of the workforce.\r\n4.	Creative, broad-reaching ideas and solutions brought to CDC projects that otherwise may have been overlooked.\r\n', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(182, 180, 'New R&D Lab engagement:  IRDA staff is currenly working with FMO staff to develop eBook version of the 2014 CDC Congressional Justificiation (CJ) document.   The eBook will be â€‹optimized to work on both the iPhone/iPad (iOS) and Android platforms - and would provide significant advantages (features and customization) over the existing PDF format.\r\n\r\n', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(183, 181, 'This project creates an industry standards-based web services for seamless real-time machine to machine communications between EIP web applications hosted at sites and CDC. The EIP Case Information Management System (CIMS) has two modules: Case Detection Service (CDS) and Case Management System (CMS).    The web application of CDS handling laboratory report entry and identifiable information management is hosted at EIP sites. The CDSâ€™s business rule engine including case criteria and EIP case repository without Personally Identifiable Information (PII) are hosted at CDC. The CMS is hosted at CDC. The project will evaluate the industry standards-based web services as a techical solution to improve communications between site-hosted and CDC-hosted components in order to improve the operation efficiency of EIP projectsâ€™ information management and data sharing and increase user satisfaction of EIP CIMS. The project will pilot and test the proposed techical solutions and provide solutions to any issues encountered during the testing.  The main challenge that can be satisfied by the R&D Lab is to create an environment where the various components can co-live for evaluation and to prototype integration.  ', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(184, 182, '', '', 'Danielle Iuliano', '', 'Karen Wong', '', 'Chun Hai (Issac) Fung', '', 'Kira Christian', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(185, 183, 'The goal of the App Testing Project is to allow stakeholders of OADC mobile applications to download and test mobile apps on their personal mobile devices. This will be accomplished by the lab posting .ipa files so app testers can download them on the fly instead of having a designated OADC resource sit with them and manually install the app. This will make the OADC app testing process more efficient as app testers can download the app builds in a timelier manner and spend more time testing the app than trying to download it.', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '');
INSERT INTO `project_summary` (`id`, `projectid`, `motivation`, `vision`, `stakeholder1`, `role1`, `stakeholder2`, `role2`, `stakeholder3`, `role3`, `stakeholder4`, `role4`, `stakeholder5`, `role5`, `stakeholder6`, `role6`, `datasources`, `steps`, `metrics`, `project_additional_info`) VALUES
(188, 186, 'We are requesting engagement of the Informatics Research Lab to help us attain tablets on a regular basis.   Our project directly supports 23 sites across the country with a questionnaire that we develop.  This survey is in constant revision and state of development due to our yearly deployment cycles.  Sites use both tablet devices as well as laptops and during testing, weâ€™ve found that tablets and laptops (sometimes each running the same operating system) behave differently. For example, screen resolution may be different across devices, and survey instructions, questions, responses, and other important information may not be consistently visible to interviewers, potentially impacting interview flow and data quality.  Therefore we cannot do all of our testing on laptops alone.  We are requesting 4 tablet-type devices to conduct user acceptability testing and ongoing survey support for the QDS 2.6.1 survey application for The Medical Monitoring Project (MMP). The survey is revised annually and acceptability testing and survey support is an ongoing activity throughout each 12-month data collection cycle. The requested tablets will not be used to collect any data. No PII or sensitive data of any kind will be collected on the requested tablets.\r\nDue to the complexity of the survey, comprehensive user acceptability testing is required by CDC staff prior to application deployment. Once the application is finalized, it is deployed to over 100 health department staff who in turn conduct more than 4000 interviews annually. The MMP interview comprises a 135-page questionnaire covering a broad range of clinical and behavioral characteristics. It includes complex skip patterns and over 1,000 independent variables. Contracted programmers code the paper questionnaire into Questionnaire Development System (QDS) v 2.6.1, Nova Research, Inc. Once deployed, the health departments require ongoing survey administration support from CDC. \r\nData are collected by state or local jurisdiction health department staff. To conduct user acceptability testing and to adequately provide survey administration support for health department staff, CDC staff needs devices similar to ones being used in the field by the health department staff. Health department staff have already purchased tablet-type devices and will being using them in the 2013 data collection cycle, which begins June 2013. Many health departments use and prefer tablet-type devices for the following reasons:\r\nâ€¢	Surveys are performed in the field outside of the health departments often in clinical settings or even in patient homes. Survey staff may travel by foot or public transportation so portability of equipment is highly valued. For example, health department staff in New York City travels on the subway with the devices and often travel from bureau to bureau throughout the day. They purchased lighter weight devices due to portability concerns. \r\nâ€¢	Some project areas report that use of tablets fosters a more informal relationship with the patient and greater rapport.  Effective rapport is critical for collection of accurate data.\r\nâ€¢	Use of a small mobile device facilitates discretion. Given the pervasiveness of stigma and discrimination surrounding HIV, this can be an important feature. \r\nâ€¢	Tablet-type devices may be less expensive for health department staff than laptops while offering adequate computing power for the task as well as the above advantages.\r\nThe MMP project requests 4 tablet-type devices that will be used by MMP staff in the testing activities described above. The tablets should be representative of what is already being deployed in the field.  Based on our recent survey of equipment in the field, we would like to buy 4 different models, specifically: the Samsung Series 7 Slate Tablet, DELL Latitude Tablet, HP (Model number 2760P) tablet, and Asus Eee Slate B121.  These devices must be:\r\nâ€¢	Supportive of QDS computer-assisted personal interviews (CAPI) version 2.6.1. Information about QDS may be found online at the following link: http://www.novaresearch.com/Products/qds/index.cfm\r\nâ€¢	 Supportive of encryption software without causing computer sluggishness or other problems.   Note: Data security standards require device data encryption (FIPS- 140-2 compliance). This raises the minimum hardware requirements for supporting QDS CAPI 2.6.1. Note that data will not be collected on the requested tablets; however, the tablets must have the capability to support encryption software to mimic the ones being used in the field.  \r\nâ€¢	Able to sustain a battery life of at least 7 to 8 hours (preferred); Optional: Interchangeable battery for back-up. \r\nâ€¢	Outfitted with at least one USB port to transfer data files (preferred); Optional:  an SD card slot for back-up.\r\nâ€¢	Rugged for field work (optional)\r\nâ€¢	Easy to carry and discrete in the field (important if interviews are not conducted in a field office)\r\n\r\nThe rough average estimated cost for these units, cases, keyboards, mice, and batteries is about $1400/unit.  We have funds available and are prepared to make the purchase immediately.\r\n', '', '23 State and local health depts.', 'Sites for deploying our surveys', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Fully tested and working surveys that can work on laptops and tablets in the field.  Impacting better quality data for our survey that in turn feeds back to prevention and future surveillance plans for HIV.'),
(187, 185, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(189, 187, 'The PHARS platform will be available for CDC programs algorithms to be utilized for delivery of actionable recommendation guidelines to a clinical setting at the point-of-care (Strengthening public health and healthcare integration for population health improvements).  The purpose of this request is to test the connectivity of an external EHR System (GE Centricity at Lehigh Valley Health Network, LVHN) to the PHARS platform where public health web services have been implemented as CDS tools with the ability to process discrete patient data elements within an algorithm resulting in a dynamically generate HTML page to be view by the clinician.', '', 'Melvin Crum', 'mcrum@cdc.gov', 'Philipp Carner', 'pcarner@cdc.gov', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(190, 188, 'We would like to create an ebook which would allow consumers to access data and other information contained in the ART National Summary Report via their mobile devices.  ', '', 'Allison Mneimneh', 'fgg8@cdc.gov', 'Sheree Boulet', 'Sbu1@cdc.gov', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(191, 189, 'The current method of creating EHR-S Functional Model (FM) profiles, using unstructured tools (spreadsheet, text processor), do not enforce moderately complex rules for creating EHR-S FM profiles leading to a very laborious manual effort that is prone to errors. Furthermore the current methods do not easily provide methods for building on top of, merging, or updating existing profiles. These challenges prove to be significant barriers in the use and adoption of the EHR-S Functional Model.  A desktop tool has been developed by HL7 to create EHR-S FM profiles (starting with the EHR-S FM Release 2), with enforced profiling rules, and exports as documents, support for and XML interchange format.  The tool is now available and starts with Enterprise Architect (EA).  Access to EA is needed to be able to run this tool. I have obtained a license for EA from HL7 for a one year period. The vision is to use this tool in the continued development of the public health functional profile sponsored by NCHS. ', 'HL7 EHR WG	Report Recipient\r\nHetty Khan	User and data supplier\r\nJohn Ritter	User and data supplier\r\n', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Ability to access Enterprise Architect (EA)\r\nAbility to load EHR-S FM into EA\r\nAbility to continue to develop the PHFP using EA\r\nAbility to generate documentation of the PHFP using EA\r\n\r\nThe PHFP will be more easily and efficiently developed, thus shortening the timeframe from development to publication as an HL7 Informative standard. This should result in a timelier standard to facilitate consideration of the inclusion of public health functional requirements into EHR systems to meet the needsd of public health.\r\n'),
(192, 190, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(194, 192, 'Todayâ€™s global health security (GHS) threats arise primarily from four sources of concern: the emergence and spread of new microbes; the globalization of travel as well as our food and medical product supply; the rise of drug resistance; and the increasing use of laboratories to engineer and inadvertently or intentionally release new and deadly pathogens and contaminated products.  Despite these challenges, two worldwide trends have created a unique window of opportunity in the pursuit of GHS objectives: new technological advances in laboratory technology, informatics, and surveillance; and greater global awareness, commitment and momentum.\r\nIn response, a small team at CDC has developed an approach that will address GHS concerns via three key outcomes over a period of four years:\r\n1)	Detection: Epidemiologic and laboratory capacity to detect and characterize any epidemic or product safety threat in every part of every country;\r\n2)	Response:  Interconnected Emergency Operations Centers with access to real-time information systems; and\r\n3)	Prevention: Internationally sourced food and drugs consumed by Americans held to the same high standards as domestically grown and manufactured products.\r\nDuring FY13, the GHS team will conduct three pilot activities in at least two countries (Uganda and Vietnam): \r\nâ€¢	Develop a national laboratory system capable of safely and accurately conducting the full range of tests necessary to detect and characterize new threats in any part of the country;\r\nâ€¢	Establish an interconnected, appropriately scaled public health Emergency Operations Center that is able to mobilize within 60 minutes to respond effectively to any public health emergency; and\r\nâ€¢	Launch a real-time information platform that is able to securely store and present visualizations of real-time outbreak data.\r\nIT team lead by Ray Ransom focuses on â€œLaunch a real-time information platform that is able to securely store and present visualizations of real-time outbreak dataâ€ with the components of Surveillance, Central Data Structure, and Data Use. One of crucial activities will be â€œDescribe one syndromic surveillance system and one comprehensive systemâ€. \r\nThis project goal is to replicate the Uganda MoH comprehensive surveillance by installing DHIS2 software and creating the access to the system for the team to better understand DHIS2 functionalities so that the IT team could recommend to the CDC GHS team if DHIS2 would meet the requirements. \r\n\r\n', 'CDC OD/GHS Team	Report recipient\r\nGHS IT Team	User\r\nCDC-Uganda	User/data supplier\r\n', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Successfully install DHIS2 with mobile component and replicate the Uganda DHIS2 surveillance environment'),
(195, 193, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(196, 194, 'GRASP and Wonder currently work together to produce maps for the Wonder application.  Wonder is currently using an older mapping technology (ArcIMS) to produce jpeg map images. ArcIMS is nolonger supported by the vendor and is being phased out.  The newer mapping technology (ArcGIS Server) requires the use of javascript to accomplish the same task (something Wonder wishes to avoid using).  This is an R&D effort with a widely accepted open source map server package to verify if Map Server will meet Wonderâ€™s business needs.', 'ATSDR/DTHHA/OD	data supplier\r\nCDC/OSELS/PHSIPO	User / data supplier\r\n', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Success will be gained by simple getting familiar with an open source server product.  Beyond that point success could grow into actual implementation for Wonder or potentially other systems.'),
(197, 195, 'GRASP is developing a second mobile application for the Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis group.  The first mobile application was developed for the iOS platform and we are now developing the same application for the Android platform.  We will require Android mobile tablet devices to test the application on as many screen resolutions and form factors as possible.', 'Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis group	User/public', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Success will be determined by the applicationâ€™s performance and functionality testing on the various Android devices.  We will be determining the max and min screen resolution that the application is capable of running on.', 'Success will be determined by the applicationâ€™s performance and functionality testing on the various Android devices.  We will be determining the max and min screen resolution that the application is capable of running on.');
